The tawny-bellied babbler is a small babbler at 13&nbsp;cm including its long round-tipped tail. The outer tail feathers are about half the length of the central tail feather. It is dark brown above and orange-buff below, with a rufous grey crown. The feathers on the forehead are stiff and the tail has cross rays and is otherwise olive brown. The throat is white in adults of the populations of peninsular India and Sri Lanka. The Sri Lankan population, however, has a larger and heavier beak and paler underparts.<ref>{{cite book|author=Whistler, Hugh| year=1949|edition=4th| publisher=Gurney and Jackson|place=London| title=Popular Handbook of Indian Birds|url=https://archive.org/stream/popularhandbooko033226mbp#page/n85/mode/2up|pages=50–51}}</ref><ref name="hbk" /><ref>{{cite journal|author=Whistler, Hugh| year=1941|title= Recognition of new subspecies of birds in Ceylon| journal= Ibis| volume= 83|issue=2|pages= 319–320|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1941.tb00626.x}}</ref>

The population on Mt. Abu is white-throated with chestnut feathers on the crown (appearing capped, as opposed to the chestnut being only on the forehead) having pale shafts. It has been proposed as a subspecies ''abuensis'' but is more often included in ''albogularis''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Harington, H.H.|year=1914|title=Notes on the Indian Timeliides and their allies (laughing thrushes, babblers, &c.) Part III. Family — Timeliidae|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30453851|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=23|pages=417–453}}</ref> Another variant form first described from Khandala Ghats as ''navarroi'' is also usually included within the range of ''albogularis''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Abdulali, H.|year=1959|title=A new white-throated race of the babbler Dumetia hyperythra|url=https://archive.org/details/journalofbombay561959bomb/page/335|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=56|pages=333–335}}</ref><ref name=fbi2>{{cite book| url=https://archive.org/details/birds01bakeiala|pages=[https://archive.org/details/birds01bakeiala/page/228 228]–230|title=Fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Birds. Volume I.|author=Baker, E.C. Stuart| place=London| year=1922| publisher=Taylor and Francis|edition=2}}</ref>

== Taxonomy and systematics ==
The species was first described by James Franklin in 1831, placed in the genus ''Timalia.'' The genus ''Dumetia'' was established by Blyth in 1852 who saw differences between it and other genera. The genus characters were in the distribution of the stiff feathers on the forehead and the shape of the bill. Modern classifications based on DNA sequences note that the species is a sister of the [[dark-fronted babbler]] and the [[chestnut-capped babbler]]. It is part of the subfamily Timaliinae.<ref>{{cite journal|author1= Gelang, M.|author2= Cibois, A.|author3= Pasquet, E.|author4= Olsson, U.|author5= Alström, P.|author6= Ericson, P. G. P.|year= 2009|title= Phylogeny of babblers (Aves, Passeriformes): major lineages, family limits and classification|journal= Zoologica Scripta|volume= 38|issue= 3|pages= 225–236|doi= 10.1111/j.1463-6409.2008.00374.x|s2cid= 21691730|url= http://www.nrm.se/download/18.2656c41712139f1fb5b80006026/Gelang+et+al+Timaliidae+ZSC+09.pdf|archive-date= 2021-12-23|access-date= 2018-10-31|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20211223003930/https://www.nrm.se/download/18.2656c41712139f1fb5b80006026/Gelang%2Bet%2Bal%2BTimaliidae%2BZSC%2B09.pdf}}</ref><ref name=phylo2012>{{cite journal|doi=10.1093/sysbio/sys027|pmid=22328569|title=Phylogeny and Biogeography of the Core Babblers (Aves: Timaliidae)|journal=Systematic Biology|volume=61|issue=4|pages=631–651|year=2012|last1=Moyle|first1=Robert G.|last2=Andersen|first2=Michael J.|last3=Oliveros|first3=Carl H.|last4=Steinheimer|first4=Frank D.|last5=Reddy|first5=Sushma|doi-access=free}}</ref>

==Distribution and habitat==

The tawny-bellied babbler is found from [[Nepal]] and north-central [[India]] to [[Sri Lanka]]. The populations in India are all intergrading and no disjunct distributions exist. Its natural habitat is scrub and tall grassland.<ref name=fbi2 /> In Sri Lanka it is found in the hills up to about 1500 m above sea level.<ref name="hbk">{{cite book|title=Handbook of the Birds of India and Pakistan. Volume 6. Cuckoo-Shrikes to Babaxes|author1=Ali, Salim|author2=Ripley, S. Dillon|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1996|edition=2|place=Delhi|pages=178–182}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Vyas, Rakesh| author2= Nair, Anil |year=1999| title= Range extension of Rufousbellied Babbler ''Dumetia hyperythra hyperythra'' (Franklin)|journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=96|issue=1|pages= 143–144|url= https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48582814}}</ref>

==Behaviour==
The tawny-bellied babbler builds its nest in a low bush, concealed in dense masses of foliage. The nest is a ball of long woven leaves of bamboo or grasses. They breed from May to September mostly during the rains. The normal clutch is three or four eggs. Both parents incubate the eggs.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Vyas, R.|title= Breeding notes on the Rufous-bellied Babbler Dumetia hyperythra| journal=Indian Birds|url=http://indianbirds.in/pdfs/IB.4.3.pdf| volume=4| issue=3| pages=114–115| year=2008}}</ref> In Sri Lanka they are thought to raise more than one brood. Like most babblers, it is not [[bird migration|migratory]], and has short rounded wings and a weak flight. A prenuptial moult takes place in January–February in the southern population. It feeds mainly on insects but also takes nectar from flowers of ''[[Bombax]]'' and ''[[Erythrina]]''. They produce cheeping, twittering or harsh chattering notes while foraging in bushes.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://avocet.zoology.msu.edu/recordings/15891 | title=Dumetia hyperythra albogularis | publisher=Avian Vocalisations Center, Michigan State University | date=22 Nov 2011 | access-date=November 14, 2015 | author=Pamela C. Rasmussen | archive-date=17 November 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117023755/http://avocet.zoology.msu.edu/recordings/15891 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://avocet.zoology.msu.edu/recordings/6614 | title=Dumetia hyperythra phillipsi | publisher=Avian Vocalisations Center, Michigan State University | date=22 Mar 2003 | access-date=November 14, 2015 | author=Deepal Warakagoda | archive-date=17 November 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117015909/http://avocet.zoology.msu.edu/recordings/6614 }}</ref> The name ''Pandi Jitta'', literally "pig bird" in [[Telugu language|Telugu]], refers to its habit of foraging under dense shrubbery in the manner of pigs.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/47310503|pages=403–404| title= A catalogue of the birds in the Museum of the Hon. East-India Company. Volume I.|author1=Horsfield, T.|author2=Moore, F.| year=1854| publisher=W.H. Allen and Co.|place=London}}</ref><ref name="hbk" />

[[Banded bay cuckoo]]s have been known to lay their eggs in the nests of tawny-bellied babblers.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1913.tb06559.x|title=The Evolution of Adaptation in Parasitic Cuckoos' Eggs|journal=Ibis|volume=55|issue=3|pages=384–398|year=2008|last1=Baker|first1=E. C. Stuart|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/26514631}}</ref> Unidentified haematozoa placed in the genus ''[[Leucocytozoon]]'' have been recorded from the blood of the species.<ref>{{cite book|title=Synoptic list of protozoa from India and their assessment of taxonomic diversity. Part 1: Parasitic protozoa. Records of the Zoological Survey of India. Occasional Paper Number 319|author1=Nandi, N.C.| author2=Das, A.K.|year=2010|url=https://archive.org/details/dli.zoological.occpapers.319|page=[https://archive.org/details/dli.zoological.occpapers.319/page/n196 191]|publisher=Zoological Survey of India}}</ref> A specimen that died in captivity was found to have microfilariae in addition to haematozoa.<ref>{{cite journal|title= Report on the deaths occurring in the Society's Gardens during the year 1929.|author=Hamerton, A.E| year=1930| journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London|pages=357–380|volume=100| issue=2|doi=10.1111/j.1096-3642.1930.tb00982.x}}</ref>

